# Transistor

> [!word] Transistor
> Transistor is a 3-layer, 3-terminal [[61-Archive/20220225130808-semiconductor|semiconductor]] device that **amplifies** or **switches** the [[61-Archive/20220408110703-current-flow|flow of current]]

The conductivity between two of the terminals is controlled by the third terminal

![../60-Meta-Attachments/b039a1189f89c22c3d21153b9fe223be.png](data:image/png;base64,)

- The tab of the water tab is like the Base in a transistor

| Name      | Symbol |
| --------- | ------ |
| Collector | C      |
| Base      | B      |
| Emitter   | E      |

- [[61-Archive/20220421150047-npn-transistor|NPN Transistor]] is **CBE**
- [[61-Archive/20220421151119-pnp-transistor|PNP Transistor]] is **EBC**

> [!note]
> Note that the arrow symbol is always on `E`

> [!important]
> Similar to [[61-Archive/20220221170726-diode|diode]], transistors always need a [[61-Archive/20220221120700-resistor|resistor]] at base (B) to avoid a very high [[61-Archive/20220408104411-current|current]].

## Transistors as Amplifiers

- $I_b$ flows only when the transistor is **turned on**
- $I_{c}\propto I_{b}, \because I_c=\beta I_b$
  - $\beta$ is in the range of 20-200, leading to an **amplification** of [[61-Archive/20220408104411-current|current]] at the _Collector_ (C) terminal side
    ![[Pasted-image-20220415124900.png|300]]

## Switch V.S. Amplifier

![[Pasted-image-20220415124937.png|Pasted image 20220415124937]]

$V_{out} \leq 5V$

When $V_{cc} \geq 5V$ , then the signal will be chopped off

A transistor can be both an **Amplifier** or a **Switch**

| Amplifier                                               | Switch                                                                       |
| ------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Have to worry about the maximum output not exceeding 5V | Don’t care what the maximum Output is, we only want the transistor to switch |

## Amplification Factors

$$


I_{E}= I_{B} +I_C


$$

### Alpha

$$
\alpha = \frac{I_{C}}{I_{E}}=\frac{\beta}{1+\beta}
$$

### Beta

> [!word] Beta
> Beta of a transistor is **the gain or amplification factor of a transistor**.
> It is the factor by which [[61-Archive/20220408104411-current|current]] is amplified in the circuit.

The value for $\beta$ is typically very large

$$
\beta = \frac{I_{C}}{I_{B}}= \frac{\alpha}{1-\alpha}
$$

> [[Pasted-image-20220418185813.png|!example]]
>
> - If a transistor has a $\beta$ of 100,
> - the $I_{B}$ is amplified by 100.
> - So if $I_b$ going into a transistor is $30\mu A$
> - the emitter [[61-Archive/20220408104411-current|current]] $I_{E}$ will be $I_{E} = (\beta +1)I_{b}= (100)30\mu A=3mA$
> - where $\beta \approx (\beta+1)$
>
> _Ref: [[Beta) of a Transistor?](http://www.learningaboutelectronics.com/Articles/What-is-beta-of-a-transistor|What is β (Beta) of a Transistor?]]_

## Transistors in Applications

![[Pasted-image-20220415151310.png|Pasted image 20220415151310]]

- When transistors are being used to amplify a signal (volume nob control), it is used in [[61-Archive/20220415142132-transistor-operation-modes#Amplification-Mode|Amplification-Mode]].
- When it is used as a switch (I/O), it is only [[61-Archive/20220415142132-transistor-operation-modes#OFF-Mode|OFF-Mode]] (Switch OFF) and [[61-Archive/20220415142132-transistor-operation-modes#Saturation-Mode|Saturation-Mode]] (Switch ON) are used.
